---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Testing">
  <main id="myContent" class="content">
    <h1>--- Test For Success ---</h1>
    <div class="newspaper">
      <div class="nobreak">
        <h1>Test Types</h1>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Development Testing</div>
          <div class="text">Testing done to understand the limits of the design space. Tests should be designed so
            that limits are reached about half the time to maximize information obtained. This way, design constraints
            are best defined. Sample sizes and test counts need to provide a good statistical basis for drawing
            conclusions.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Verification Testing</div>
          <div class="text">Testing done to verify that functional requiremenst are met. Test failures at this point
            should be rare and carefully evaluated if they occur.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Reliability Testing</div>
          <div class="text">Testing done to determine and/or verify expected product life. Testing must be done to
            failue to be sure that product strengths are well understood.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="nobreak">
        <h1>Statistical Terms</h1>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Statistical Significance</div>
          <div class="text">Statistical signifiance should always be considered when designing test plans and evaluating
            results. Consideration should be given to the following:</div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Sample Size (<span class="highlight">n</span>)</div>
          <div class="text">Small sample size can contribute to design flaw escapes due to incorrect conclusions due to
            high Beta error. Beta error is inversly proportional to sample size.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Minimum (<span class="highlight">p-value</span>) for rejecting the null hypothesis
          </div>
          <div class="text">This should be a business derive value where test cost is traded off for lower Alpha error.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">- Match tools to data</div>
          <div class="text">- continuous v.s. discrete</div>
          <div class="text">- Normally distributed v.s. Non-normal</div>
          <div class="text">- Correct number of <span class="highlight">factors</span> and <span
              class="highlight">levels</span>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="news-card glow-box">
          <div class="heading">Verification Medhods</div>
          <div class="text">Once requirements are understood, the methods for verification should be defined. These
            methods must include <span class="highlight">specific test procedures</span> to be used, the <span
              class="highlight">units of measure</span>, and the <epan class="highlight">accoptance criteria</epan>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>